<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-631-390 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 631 390.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  April 23 1991 v5 n16 p9(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Macweek 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GEOvista makes presentation maps. (from Newton Technology Inc.)andO;(product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cohen, Raines.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Newton Technology Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (Computer programs)GEOvista (Geographic information system) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Software PackagesMapsDesktop PublishingGeographic Information SystemsProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Raines CohenandM;Wellesley, Mass.andP;  -- Although informative illustrated maps often lie at theheart of a successful presentation, most Mac desktop mapping tools areoptimized for printed output or advanced cartography instead of easy, rapidcreation.andM;That's not the case with GEOvista, a new mapping package from NewtonTechnology Inc.andP;  Designed to help users create maps based on their own data,the $249 application can fill in map segments -- such as U.S.andP;  states -- withcross-hatch and variable-dot-density black-and-white patterns, as well as32-bit color.andM;U.S.andP;  Geological Survey and U.S.andP;  Census state outline files are suppliedwith the program.andP;  Outline files for North America and the world, to be soldseparately, will be available within three to six months, the company said.andM;Maps as large as 3 feet per side are supported.andP;  They can be exported in PICTformat or, for smaller files, in Paint format.andP;  GEOvista can import data onlyby using the Clipboard.andM;Newton Technology Inc. is at 70 Walnut St., Wellesley, Mass.andP;  02181.andP;  Phone(617) 239-8202 or (800) 835-3031; fax (617) 944-0197.andO;</TEXT></DOC>